#read dataset
anscombe_quartet <- readRDS("anscombe_quartet.rds")
str(anscombe_quartet)
## tibble [44  3] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)
##  $ dataset: chr [1:44] "dataset_1" "dataset_1" "dataset_1" "dataset_1" ...
##  $ x      : num [1:44] 10 8 13 9 11 14 6 4 12 7 ...
##  $ y      : num [1:44] 8.04 6.95 7.58 8.81 8.33 ...
# what does the function str() do? 
#To show the structure of the dataset.

#check some summary statistics:

anscombe_quartet %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_x    = mean(x),
    mean_y    = mean(y),
    min_x     = min(x),
    min_y     = min(y),
    max_x     = max(x),
    max_y     = max(y),
    crrltn    = cor(x, y)
  )
## # A tibble: 4  8
##   dataset   mean_x mean_y min_x min_y max_x max_y crrltn
##   <chr>      <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 dataset_1      9   7.50     4  4.26    14 10.8   0.816
## 2 dataset_2      9   7.50     4  3.1     14  9.26  0.816
## 3 dataset_3      9   7.5      4  5.39    14 12.7   0.816
## 4 dataset_4      9   7.50     8  5.25    19 12.5   0.817
# what do the summary statistics tell us about the different datasets? 
# Mean of X: All datasets have a mean of x values at 9.
# Mean of Y: All datasets have a mean of y values close to 7.5.
# Minimum of X: The minimum x values are 4 for the first three datasets and 8 for dataset 4.
# Minimum of Y: The minimum y values vary slightly across the datasets, with the smallest value in dataset 2.
# Maximum of X: All datasets have the maximum x value at 14.
# Maximum of Y: The maximum y values vary, with dataset 3 having the highest maximum value.
# Correlation (crrltn): All datasets have a correlation coefficient of approximately 0.816, showing a strong positive linear relationship between x and y.
# plot the data with ggplot:

require(ggplot2)

 ggplot(anscombe_quartet, aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",formula = "y ~ x") +
  facet_wrap(~dataset)

#save the plot

ggsave("anscombe_quartet.png", width = 20, height = 20, units = "cm")

# what do the plots tell us about the different datasets? 
## Despite these similarities in summary statistics, the actual distributions of the points in each dataset can be different. Summary statistics can be identical for datasets that are very different in structure and appearance.

# describe the relationship between x and y in the different datasets. 
# would linear regression be an appropriate statistical model to analyse the x-y relationship in each dataset?

#Dataset 1:

#The relationship between x and y is linear with points scattered roughly evenly around the regression line.
#Linear regression can be applied for this dataset as the data points follow a linear trend without extreme outliers.

#Dataset 2:

#The relationship is non-linear, the points follow a curved pattern.
#A linear regression model would not be appropriate. A non-linear model would be more suitable.

#Dataset 3:

#The relationship appears linear except for one outlier.
#Linear regression can be appropriate if the outlier can be excluded.

#Dataset 4:

#There is no relationship between x and y, in the graph the only one outlier creates the spurious correlation.
#Linear regression can not be applied due to the lack of a linear relationship.

# what conclusions can you draw for the plots and summary statistics? 
# Datasets with the same summary statistics can have significantly different distributions and relationships between variables.
# Summary statistics per se is therefore not enough, visualizing data is important to understand the underlying relationships and assess the suitability of statistical models.

PROBLEM 2

# load in the datasaurus dataset
datasaurus_dozen <- readRDS("datasaurus_dozen.rds")

# explore the dataset 
#show dataset structure
str(datasaurus_dozen)
## tibble [1,846  3] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)
##  $ dataset: chr [1:1846] "dino" "dino" "dino" "dino" ...
##  $ x      : num [1:1846] 55.4 51.5 46.2 42.8 40.8 ...
##  $ y      : num [1:1846] 97.2 96 94.5 91.4 88.3 ...
##  - attr(*, "spec")=
##   .. cols(
##   ..   dataset = col_character(),
##   ..   x = col_double(),
##   ..   y = col_double()
##   .. )
# how many rows and columns does the datasaurus_dozen file have? 
#rows = 1,846 rows
#columns = 3 columns
# plot the dataset 
require(ggplot2)
ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y)) + #plot dataset
  geom_point() +  #add scattered points for each x, y point 
  facet_wrap(~dataset)  #seperate plots to be based on each panel

# calculate the correlations and summary statistics for x and y in all datasets: 
datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(
    mean_x    = mean(x), #calculates the mean of 'x' in dataset;
    mean_y    = mean(y), #calculates the mean of 'y' in dataset;
    min_x     = min(x), #gives smallest x value
    min_y     = min(y), #gives smallest y value
    max_x     = max(x), #gives largest x value
    max_y     = max(y), #gives largest y value
    crrltn    = cor(x, y) #calculates correlation coefficient between x and y
  )

# Plot the relationships between x and y in each dataset including the line of best fit.
 ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",formula = "y ~ x") +
  facet_wrap(~dataset)

# what conclusions can you draw for the plots and summary statistics? 
## Although there are similar statistical summaries, the underlying relationships are different.
##The plots demonstrate that linear regression would not be suitable for most of the datasets, as the actual patterns of data points do not follow a linear line.
